Class CppHashSet

java.lang.Object
  com.versant.trans.SCO
      com.versant.util.CppHashSet
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable
public class CppHashSet
extends SCO
implements java.lang.Cloneable, java.io.Serializable

This is a Second Class Object used only as an attribute in a persistent instance of a C++ defined class when you share objects and classes created from the VERSANT C++ language interface with the transparent Java binding.

This class is based on the HashSet class in the java.util package of JDK 1.2.

A set that contains no duplicate elements. More formally, CppHashSets contain no pair of elements e1 and e2 such that e1.equals(e2), and at most one null element. As implied by its name, this interface models the mathematical set abstraction.

All constructors must create a CppHashSet that contain no duplicate elements. This set is backed by a hash table (actually a CppHashMap). It offers constant time performance for the basic operations (add, remove, contains and size), assuming the hash function disperses the elements properly among the buckets. This CppHashSet does not permit the null element.

Note that this implementation is not synchronized.

If multiple threads access a CppHashSet concurrently, and at least one of the threads modifies the CppHashSet, it must be synchronized externally. This is typically accomplished by synchronizing on some object that naturally encapsulates the CppHashSet.

The Iterators returned by CppHashSet's iterator method are fail-fast: if the HashSet is modified at any time after the Iterator is created, except through the Iterator's own remove method, the Iterator throws a RuntimeException. Thus, in the face of concurrent modification, the Iterator fails quickly and cleanly, rather than risking arbitrary, non-deterministic behavior at an undetermined time in the future.

equals in class java.lang.Object
Parameters:
o - Object to be compared for equality with this CppHashSet.

This implementation first checks if the specified Object is this CppHashSet. If so, it returns true. Then, it checks if the specified Object is a CppHashSet whose size is identical to the size of this CppHashSet. If not, it returns false. If so, it returns containsAll().

Returns:
true if the specified Object is equal to this CppHashSet.

hashCode

public int hashCode()
Returns the hash code value for this CppHashSet.

The hash code of a CppHashSet is the sum of the hashCodes of the elements in the CppHashSet. Therefore, s1.equals(s2) implies that s1.hashCode()==s2.hashCode() for any two Sets s1 and s2, as required by the general contract of Object.hashCode.

This implementation enumerates over the CppHashSet calls hashCode on each element in the CppHashSet, and adds up the results.

Overrides:
hashCode in class java.lang.Object

toArray

public java.lang.Object[] toArray()
Returns an array that contains all of the elements in this CppHashSet.

If the CppHashSet makes any guarantees, as to what order its Iterator returns its elements, this method must return the elements in the same order.

The returned array will be "safe" because no references to it are maintained by the CppHashSet. (In other words, this method must allocate a new array even if the CppHashSet is backed by an Array). Thus, the caller is free to modify the returned array.

This implementation allocates the array to be returned, and iterates over the elements in the CppHashSet. Starting with element 0, it stores each object reference in the next consecutive element of the array.
